  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div xml:id="KT292-kilavi">
        <p type="edition">tōḻi iravukkuṟikkaṇ ciṟaippuṟamākak kāppumikuti colliyatu. </p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">The confidante speaking about the increase in guarding,
          while [he] is behind the hedge at the night tryst. </p>
      </div>

      <div xml:id="KT292">
        <lg type="edition">
          <l> maṇṇiya ceṉṟa voṇṇuta larivai</l>
          <l> puṉaṟaru pacuṅkāy tiṉṟataṉ ṟappaṟ</l>
          <l> koṉpatiṟ ṟoṉpatu kaḷiṟṟō ṭavaṇiṟai</l>
          <l> poṉcey pāvai koṭuppavuṅ koḷḷāṉ</l>
          <l> peṇkolai purinta naṉṉaṉ pōla</l>
          <l> varaiyā niraiyattuc celīiyarō vaṉṉai</l>
          <l> yorunā</l>
          <l> ṇakaimuka viruntiṉaṉ vanteṉap</l>
          <l> pakaimuka vūriṟ ṟuñcalō vilaḷē.</l>
        </lg>

        <lg type="alternate" sameAs="6+8b">
          <l>May mother go to hell forever ...</l>
          <l>Is she [really] going to be sleepless ...?</l>
        </lg>

        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
          <l>Mother, who, like a village facing the enemy, doesn't sleep at all, <note place="foot"> <term xml:lang="ta"> tuñcal-ō ilaḷ </term>: the <term xml:lang="ta"> -ō </term> presumably has to be taken here in the function of demarcating the topic: "as for sleeping, not she".   </note> </l>
          <l rend="indent2">because a guest with smiling face has come one day</l>
          <l>– may she forever go to hell</l>
          <l rend="indent">like Naṉṉaṉ, who wanted the murder of a woman,</l>
          <l rend="indent">without taking, even when it was offered [him], a gold-made image</l>
          <l rend="indent2">of her full weight together with nine [times] nine elephant bulls,</l>
          <l rend="indent3">[for] her error that the young woman with bright forehead,</l>
          <l rend="indent3">who had gone to bath, had eaten a green unripe fruit given</l>
          <l rend="indent8">by the flood.<note place="foot"> The legend rather alluded to than told here seems to have no fuller version, at least not in Caṅkam literature. What is made of it by tradition is the story of king Naṉṉaṉ, who had a woman killed because she had unknowingly eaten a fruit from a favoured mango tree under his protection. Even a high ransom of gold and elephants would not appease him. Because of this atrocity he was fought and ultimately defeated by his enemies, the Kōcars (who are alluded to in KT 15 and 73).  </note>   </l>


        </lg>
      </div>
